    title="A personal AI layer"
    subtitle="OpenClaw and a Cowork-backed assistant: two tools, one job description."
    abstract="The category of work that benefits most from a personal AI is the boring, predictable, persistent kind: morning briefings, calendar triage, mail filtering, follow-up nudges, the long tail of life admin. We describe a two-tool stack that approaches the problem from both ends. <strong>OpenClaw</strong> is a self-hosted local agent running as a macOS LaunchAgent, exposing skills (calendar, mail, weather, briefings) to a Telegram bot the author can address from anywhere. <strong>Personal AI Assistant</strong> is the same job description executed inside Claude Cowork, taking advantage of richer reasoning, longer-running tasks, and direct access to the author's MCP-connected services. The two are deliberately not unified: each plays to a different cost / latency / reasoning trade-off, and treating them as one tool would force the wrong compromise on both."
